<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,1018,1981]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,398,1198,1225]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Taxonomic note.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Emden, F. I. van" box="[407,569,1198,1225]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref17694" refString="Emden, F. I. van (1958) Muscidae collected on the Cape Verde Islands. Results of the Zoological Expedition of Professor Dr. Hakan Lindberg to the Cape Verde Islands in the winter 1953 - 54. No 24. Commentationes biologicae, 20, 1 - 18." type="journal article" year="1958">Emden (1958)</bibRefCitation>
proposed the subspecies 
<taxonomicName box="[862,1394,1199,1225]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="riparia" subGenus="Calliophrys" subSpecies="capoverdica">
<emphasis box="[862,1394,1199,1225]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Limnophora (Calliophrys) riparia capoverdica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the 
<collectingCountry box="[192,321,1235,1261]" name="Cape Verde" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Cape Verde</collectingCountry>
population of the widespread Palearctic 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1824" box="[779,887,1235,1260]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="riparia">
<emphasis box="[779,887,1235,1260]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">L. riparia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based on some differences in colour of the head and mesonotum and length of the aristal branches. On direct comparison of 
<typeStatus box="[999,1047,1271,1297]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">type</typeStatus>
specimens (see above) with specimens from the Canary Islands and various European countries I found that the colour falls within the variation of the nominal species and that the difference pertaining to the arista is non-existing. Therefore, 
<taxonomicName authority="Emden" authorityName="Emden" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="riparia" subGenus="Calliophrys" subSpecies="capoverdica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Limnophora (Calliophrys) riparia capoverdica</emphasis>
Emden
</taxonomicName>
is here considered as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fallen)" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1824" box="[867,1190,1379,1406]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="riparia" status="syn. nov.">
<emphasis box="[867,1092,1379,1405]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Limnophora riparia</emphasis>
(Fallén)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1202,1305,1379,1405]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1202,1305,1379,1405]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">syn. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="118" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,1018,1981]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1414,1440]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small to medium sized, wing length 
<quantity box="[755,886,1414,1441]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.65" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="3.8" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" unit="mm" value="4.65" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="3.8">3.8‒5.5mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis box="[899,966,1415,1441]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Male:</emphasis>
Arista short-pubescent, longest branches not quite as long greatest width of arista. Frons broad, flat, near horizontal, widening towards lunule; vertex and fronto-orbital plates in dorsal view greyish brown pruinose, long frontal triangle silvery white pruinose, frontal vitta matt black. Parafacial plates silvery white with a black patch on vibrissal area. Fronto-orbital plate with 2 orbital and 3 frontal setae. Frons lying behind moderately produced facial margin. Mesonotum light grey pruinose with three broad, dark brown stripes that occasionally merge behind the suture and dark patches at laterobasal corners of scutellum. Dorsocentral setae 4 behind the suture; presutural acrostichal field bare except for two close-set rows of setulae. Calypteres dirty whitish, wing membrane brownish tinged; vein R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1023,1049,1685,1699]" fontSize="6" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">4+5</subScript>
on basal half between radial node and crossvein r‒m with 3‒4 dorsal setulae. Mid femur with (1‒)2 subapical 
<emphasis box="[1021,1049,1703,1729]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">pd</emphasis>
setae and a few 
<emphasis box="[1242,1268,1703,1728]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">pv</emphasis>
setae on basal third; mid tibia with 1 
<emphasis box="[404,432,1739,1765]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">pd</emphasis>
seta near middle. Hind femur with 3‒5 
<emphasis box="[880,906,1739,1764]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">av</emphasis>
setae on distal half, without 
<emphasis box="[1229,1255,1739,1764]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">pv</emphasis>
setae. Sternite I bare. Sternite V and hypopygium as in 
<figureCitation box="[595,729,1775,1801]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[174,1394,205,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-19@18.[157,1430,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 10. Limnophora quaterna (Loew) (A‒C), L. riparia (Fallén) (D‒F). Males. Sternite V (A, F); hypopygium, caudal (B, E) and lateral (C, D). Same scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4671838" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4671838/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Figs 10D‒F</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis box="[741,834,1775,1801]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Female:</emphasis>
Overall larger but otherwise very similar to the male even in respect to the head characteristics. Ovipositor (
<figureCitation box="[761,868,1811,1837]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1973,1997]" captionTargetBox="[195,1374,194,1923]" captionTargetId="figure-15@21.[182,1406,181,1949]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 12. Limnophora exigua (Wiedemann) (A, B), L. obsignatula sp. nov. (C), L. riparia (Fallén) (D). Ovipositor, lateral (A, C, D) and dorsal (B). Same scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4671844" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4671844/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Figs 12D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[879,927,1811,1837]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[174,1374,261,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-19@22.[163,1424,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 13. Limnophora paneliusi (Emden) (A), L. riparia (Fallén) (B). Ovipositor, distal part, lateral. Arrow: dorsal hind marginal setulae on T VIII. Abbreviations: Acc scl = accessory sclerite; Ce = cercus; Ep = epiproct; Hy = hypoproct; St = sternite; T = tergite. Same scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4671848" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4671848/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">13B</figureCitation>
) most similar to those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stein" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[1211,1360,1811,1837]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bipunctata">
<emphasis box="[1211,1360,1811,1837]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">L. bipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stein" baseAuthorityYear="1908" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidithorax">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">L. nitidithorax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the lateral seta on tergite VIII is accompanied by 1‒3 fine setulae. See 
<tableCitation box="[1129,1212,1847,1873]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="6.[151,214,575,601]" captionTargetBox="[159,1920,612,1616]" captionTargetId="graphics-40@6.[151,1932,752,1617]" captionText="Table 1. Matrix of 11 characters and their states (different colours) derived from the ovipositor and scored for 12 species of Limnophora." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF496603027CFFDB57B3FDBAF984772C" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" tableUuid="DF496603027CFFDB57B3FDBAF984772C">Table 1</tableCitation>
for more ovipositor characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="118" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,1018,1981]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1918,1944]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[362,493,1919,1945]" name="Cape Verde" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Cape Verde</collectingCountry>
Is.: São Nicolau; Canary Islands: Tenerife, La Gomera and La Palma; Madeira. A widespread Palearctic species ranging west‒east from Macaronesia to 
<collectingCountry box="[939,1053,1955,1981]" name="Tajikistan" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Tajikistan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
